The impairment charge was recorded in its retail banking reporting unit, and is a result of the prolonged delay in the full recovery of the U.S. economy and the impact of that delay on earnings estimates. The impairment charge is a non-cash item, and had minimal impact on RBS Citizens, N.A.'s regulatory capital ratios and liquidity. The original second quarter 2013 Call Report filed for RBS Citizens, N.A. on July 30, 2013 was amended on August 29, 2013 to reflect this goodwill impairment.

The new method of accounting for the receivable recognizes an offsetting receivable from the FDIC at the time problem loan expenses are incurred, based on the documented expectation that a qualifying loss event and reimbursement will occur in the future. The new method of accounting is analogous to indemnification asset accounting, and is more consistent in matching revenue with expense. This assessment is based upon management's estimate of future taxable income, projected using internal projections which consider historical performance, various internal estimates and assumptions, as well as certain external data, all of which management believes to be reasonable. Therefore, as of September 30, 2013, management recorded a reversal of the valuation allowance of $73.9 million previously carried to offset the net deferred tax asset.
